This lively outdoor bar under a hut was a blast. I love the tropical decors and the live music they had. It was pretty crowded so we ended up sitting by the bar. Service was quick. Pina colada was served in a fresh pineapple. I almost finished by the end of the night. The singer for the night got people to go up and dance to all the old hits she did a cover of. So many locals join in from young to old.  This bar definitely attracts a fun crowd. Beside dancing, many people are just here to relax and hang out with company. It was also convenience for us because it was in Waikiki so it wasn't too bad of a walk. Glad we stumbled upon this bar. A great way to start off the vacation.

Yes, this place is a tourist trap. Yes, you may initially cringe when you walk in. Yes, it has a menu full of drinks that sound generic.  However, trust me when I say you just have to sit down, order a drink, and get settled in for the live music.  Bit by bit, you slowly realize that you're having a blast. The singer has an incredible voice and makes the experience interactive, the people all around you are extremely friendly and everyone is dancing and tapping their feet along with the music. The drinks themselves while generically named taste refreshing and balanced.  I came here at 730pm on a Friday night with my girlfriend and her parents. We had planned on leaving at 815-830pm after we finished a drink. We ended up staying past 10pm, dancing and just having a great time.  I know this place isn't for everyone and I'm sure the ambiance changes based on who's currently there in the moment. However, just keep an open mind and take a chance. You may end up having way more fun than you thought you would!

Have just been here with some friends who are also reviewing this place as we have a big warning. We arranged to meet up for drinks here at around 10pm as the advised closing time was 12pm. We arrived in good spirits and walked in the front door about to enjoy a few drinks. Within seconds of entering a grumpy voice greeted us saying excuse me tourists we are closed. We replied by saying sorry sir we are here for a few drinks and will be gone by 12pm. The bar tender then confronted my female friend in an aggressive manner and said we are sick of you foreigners coming here and thinking you can do what we want. I felt incredible embarrassment and my female friend was in tears as we left. This made me feel sick right to my core and the first time I've felt discrimination or racism head on. Never go to this place, ever I can't stress this enough.

The second night I was told it was “closed” at 11.18pm when it states it was closed at 12am. All I wanted was a drink but they told me the tills were closed. Not a great thing to do with over 40mins left of trading. Especially considering people were being served inside even though the till was closed apparently. Not impressed, what a scorn on an otherwise wonderful trip.

Great tiki bar hidden off the main drag in Waikiki. This place really shines with its decor and atmosphere - but the drinks are mediocre and very overpriced. The “real pina colada” is served in a real pineapple but lacks the sweetness one usually associates with a pina, tasting about like a shot of rum in a cored pineapple. Truly, this isn’t a $17 drink (really $20 with tax and tip!) The Mai Thai is similar - very strong, like strawberry kool aid with two shots of vodka. The music can also be ear-splitting, we actually left without ordering the first time we visited because we couldn’t even hear each other talk. If we come back here again, it’ll be for the atmosphere and live music - as long as we don’t need earplugs!

Our family group of five were disappointed in food and drinks. We came before dinner rush on a Saturday so it wasn’t very crowded (usually a good thing).  Cons: We ordered two fish and chips and the amount of fries was laughable; they served such small portions, like they were rationing their fries! Server never came back around after dropping off food so we couldn’t ask about it. My sister ordered the pineapple coconut cocktail and while it looked pretty, the drink mix was not very good and it was watery. I ordered the ‘tipsy tiki’ cocktail and it also tasted watered down (like when ice sits in a drink too long). Son ordered the hamburger and the meat was very overcooked. Servers were shy and nice but overall staff was not very attentive or helpful. They don’t have kids menus either. Cutlery is all plasticware, disposable plates, styrofoam water cups and disposable plastic drinking cups. Felt more like a picnic :-/  Pros: the live music was fun playing 60s and 70s music, and the decor made it feel festive.  But overall, an overpriced tourist bar that we probably won’t come back to.

My boyfriend and I are were walking down the street without a purpose, just enjoying the warm night air of Waikiki.  As we walked by the first entrance for Cuckoo Coconuts we heard my new favourite band, The Oldies and Goodies Band. We peeked inside and saw people dancing and having a good time but we were hungry and heading for hotpot so we started walking on.  Thank all of the Tikis God's that there was a second entrance door because as we walked by again, we could not resist the sounds of The Oldies and Goodies Band and the opportunity to people watch (bc there were a lot of people ripping up the little D floor) so we went in for a drink.  Our vacation in Waikiki is not done yet, butletmetellya....our night at Cuckoo Coconuts was the BEST TIME EVER. We drank out of pineapples (their drinks are delicious!) and we danced our hearts out and sang along with the band. We initially went in for one pineapple drink and ended up staying for 2.5 more hours just to dance to our new favourite band.  Guys and gals, go here. Do it. Trust me. Especially on Monday and Thursday nights when The Oldies and Goodies Band is playing. You are guaranteed going to have a great time. The drinks were tasty and reasonably priced, the staff were awesome and friendly, the Tiki atmosphere was wickedly cheesy and the band was the best!

The atmosphere is friendly and fun. But poor service. It took a long time to wait for the waiter to come over and take the order. The food took a long time to come out as well- and the order was not right. What we recieved was good tasting though (one of the poke bowls) so it was fine. However, we never were served water! I raised my hand for five minutes, trying to call attention over to get a glass of water. Finally when I was close to being done eating I was served a drink. I also got an alcoholic beverage which was actually very good.  This place is also NOT ENVIRONMENTALLY FRIENDLY.  I would never go again because of how wasteful it is. If you care about the planet at all, go somewhere else. Nothing is reusable. They use plastic cups for alcoholic drinks, styrofoam cups for water, plastic cutlery, paper plates etc for serving. It is incredibly disappointing.  Take your money elsewhere. It is nothing special and very wasteful. You can get delicious food and drinks with better service and less waste at just about any restaurant in Waikiki.

What a great 'hole-in-the-wall' place.  The atmosphere is margaritaville meets Hawaiian beach comber.  The mishmash of umbrellas decorated with lights, mobiles and other tropical island themed arty pieces lead your eyes across the space to look at the Tiki carvings, one is thirty feet tall, the straw-roofed bar, and the beach murals on every wall.  The food is Hawaiian bar/comfort food, the drinks are generous and extravagent, served in pineapples and coconuts.  The band was awesome, fantastic music, mostly old classic rock and some pop and Latin to round. It out.  They put on quite a show in addition to their music but I won't say more and give away their surprises.  I'm definitely going back.

Easy to get to, in the middle of the action, yet tucked away like a secret hideaway! Super fun, great live music with just the right amount of fun audience interaction, and of course, alcohol and food. Best thing is the Pina Coladas in a pineapple, there's also a more affordable version in a glass for those on a budget. This place makes me want to stay and become a local! LOVE IT!
